05342nam a22008175i 9789048552146DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485521467 a10.1515/97890485521462doi  a(DE-B1597)572587  a(OCoLC)1199365910  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0150302bisacsh1 aHeyam, Kit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Reputation of Edward II, 1305-1697 :bA Literary Transformation of History /cKit Heyam. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (348 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGendering the Late Medieval and Early Modern World ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1. Riot, Sodomy, and Minions -- t2. From Goats to Ganymedes -- t3. Edward II and Piers Gaveston -- t4. 'Is it not strange that he is thus bewitch'd?' -- t5. Edward II as Political Exemplum -- t6. 'No escape now from a life full of suffering' -- t7. Beyond Sexual Mimesis -- tConclusion: The Literary Transformation of History -- tAppendix: Accounts of and allusions to Edward II's reign , composed 1305-1697 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring his lifetime and the four centuries following his death, King Edward II (1307-1327) acquired a reputation for having engaged in sexual and romantic relationships with his male favourites, and having been murdered by penetration with a red-hot spit. This book provides the first account of how this reputation developed, providing new insights into the processes and priorities that shaped narratives of sexual transgression in medieval and early modern England. In doing so, it analyses the changing vocabulary of sexual transgression in English, Latin and French; the conditions that created space for sympathetic depictions of same-sex love; and the use of medieval history in early modern political polemic. It also focuses, in particular, on the cultural impact of Christopher Marlowe's Edward II (c.1591-92). Through such close readings of poetry and drama, alongside chronicle accounts and political pamphlets, it demonstrates that Edward's medieval and early modern afterlife was significantly shaped by the influence of literary texts and techniques. A 'literary transformation' of historiographical methodology is, it argues, an apposite response to the factors that shaped medieval and early modern narratives of the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aHomosexualityzGreat BritainxHistory. 4aEarly Modern Period. 4aGender Studies. 4aHistory. 4aLiterary History and Criticism. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Tudor & Elizabethan Era (1485-1603).2bisacsh  aEdward II, sexuality, homosexuality, historiography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048552146zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048552146423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048552146.jpg  a978-3-11-068955-6  